## Implementation Plan: Full CRUD for IncidentDashboard

### Overview of Changes

Three files need changes. One file needs new CSS rules appended. The rest of the app is untouched.

| File | Change Type |
|---|---|
| `server/models/IncidentLog.js` | Add 4 new Sequelize fields |
| `server/routes/incident.js` | Add `POST /` and `PATCH /:id` with verifyToken |
| `client/src/pages/IncidentDashboard.jsx` | Replace static state with real API calls; add Create, Edit, and Delete Confirm modals |
| `client/src/css/IncidentDashboard.css` | Append new `inc-` classes for the two new modals |

---

## File 1: `server/models/IncidentLog.js`

### What changes

Add four columns after `confidence_score`. The `paranoid: true` (soft delete) is already in place and must stay.

```js
severity: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(20),
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: 'Medium'
    // Values the frontend uses: 'Critical' | 'High' | 'Medium' | 'Low'
},
source: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(50),
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: 'Facial Recognition'
    // Values: 'Facial Recognition' | 'Object Detection' | 'Manual'
},
resolutionStatus: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(50),
    allowNull: false,
    defaultValue: 'Active'
    // Values: 'Active' | 'Investigating' | 'Escalated to Security' | 'Cleared'
},
notes: {
    type: DataTypes.TEXT,
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: ''
}
```

### Why these types

- `severity` and `source` are short strings — `STRING(20)` and `STRING(50)` match the existing `status` column pattern.
- `resolutionStatus` needs up to `'Escalated to Security'` (22 chars) so `STRING(50)` gives safe headroom.
- `notes` is free-form text, `TEXT` matches `SecurityLogs.js` pattern for `reviewNotes`.
- All four are `allowNull: true` or have a `defaultValue` because the existing AI `scan-frame` route calls `IncidentLog.create(...)` with only `camera_location`, `status`, `person_name`, `confidence_score`. Adding non-nullable columns without defaults would break that route.

### Sequelize `alter: true` behaviour

`server/index.js` runs `db[name].sync({ alter: true })` on startup for every model. Adding these four columns to the model definition is sufficient — Sequelize will issue `ALTER TABLE incident_logs ADD COLUMN ...` automatically on next server start with no manual migration required.

---

## File 2: `server/routes/incident.js`

### Import addition (top of file)

```js
const { verifyToken } = require('../middlewares/auth');
```

### New route 1 — `POST /` (manual incident creation)

Place this immediately after the `scan-frame` block, before `GET /`.

```
POST /api/incident/
Auth: verifyToken (FM only via role check inside handler, following the security.js PATCH pattern)
Body: { camera_location, status, source, severity, person_name?, confidence_score?, notes? }
```

Handler logic:
1. Destructure body fields.
2. Validate that `camera_location`, `status`, `source`, and `severity` are present; return `400` with a descriptive error if missing.
3. `IncidentLog.create({ camera_location, status, source, severity, person_name: person_name || null, confidence_score: confidence_score || null, notes: notes || '', resolutionStatus: 'Active' })`.
4. Return `201` with the created record.

```js
router.post("/", verifyToken, async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const { camera_location, status, source, severity, person_name, confidence_score, notes } = req.body;

        if (!camera_location || !status || !source || !severity) {
            return res.status(400).json({ error: "camera_location, status, source, and severity are required." });
        }

        const newLog = await IncidentLog.create({
            camera_location,
            status,
            source,
            severity,
            person_name: person_name || null,
            confidence_score: confidence_score ? parseFloat(confidence_score) : null,
            notes: notes || '',
            resolutionStatus: 'Active'
        });

        res.status(201).json(newLog);
    } catch (err) {
        console.error("Failed to create incident:", err);
        res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to create incident log." });
    }
});
```

### New route 2 — `PATCH /:id` (update resolutionStatus and notes)

Place this immediately before `DELETE /:id`.

```
PATCH /api/incident/:id
Auth: verifyToken
Body: { resolutionStatus?, notes? }
```

Handler logic:
1. Find by PK; return `404` if not found.
2. Validate `resolutionStatus` is one of the allowed values if provided.
3. `log.update({ resolutionStatus, notes })` — only update fields that are present in the body (use nullish coalescing to fall back to current values).
4. Return `200` with updated record.

```js
const ALLOWED_RESOLUTION_STATUSES = ['Active', 'Investigating', 'Escalated to Security', 'Cleared'];

router.patch("/:id", verifyToken, async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const log = await IncidentLog.findByPk(req.params.id);
        if (!log) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Incident not found." });

        const { resolutionStatus, notes } = req.body;

        if (resolutionStatus && !ALLOWED_RESOLUTION_STATUSES.includes(resolutionStatus)) {
            return res.status(400).json({
                error: `resolutionStatus must be one of: ${ALLOWED_RESOLUTION_STATUSES.join(', ')}.`
            });
        }

        await log.update({
            resolutionStatus: resolutionStatus ?? log.resolutionStatus,
            notes: notes !== undefined ? notes : log.notes
        });

        res.status(200).json(log);
    } catch (err) {
        console.error("Failed to update incident:", err);
        res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to update incident log." });
    }
});
```

### Existing `DELETE /:id` — add `verifyToken`

The existing delete handler has no auth. Per requirements, write routes get `verifyToken`. Change the signature:

```js
router.delete("/:id", verifyToken, async (req, res) => { ... });
```

The `GET /` and `GET /:id` routes intentionally stay without auth (read-only, consistent with existing behaviour).

---

## File 3: `client/src/pages/IncidentDashboard.jsx`

This is the largest change. The structure of the existing JSX (filter bar, stat cards, table, detail modal) stays completely intact. We are adding new state, replacing the initial `useState(STATIC_INCIDENTS)` with an API-fed state, and adding three new modal render blocks.

### 3a. New imports

```js
import { useState, useMemo, useEffect, useCallback } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';
```

`useEffect` and `useCallback` replace the missing import. `axios` is used throughout the app with the exact pattern already described in requirements.

### 3b. Keep `STATIC_INCIDENTS` array as-is

It stays in the file for seeding. The `T()` helper stays too.

### 3c. New state variables

Replace the existing single `useState(STATIC_INCIDENTS)` line and add alongside existing state:

```js
// API state
const [incidents, setIncidents]    = useState([]);       // was: useState(STATIC_INCIDENTS)
const [loading, setLoading]        = useState(true);
const [apiError, setApiError]      = useState('');

// Create modal
const [showCreate, setShowCreate]  = useState(false);
const [createForm, setCreateForm]  = useState({
    camera_location: '',
    status: 'UNAUTHORIZED_ACCESS',
    source: 'Facial Recognition',
    severity: 'Medium',
    person_name: '',
    confidence_score: '',
    notes: ''
});
const [createSaving, setCreateSaving] = useState(false);

// Edit mode on the detail modal
const [editMode, setEditMode]      = useState(false);
const [editForm, setEditForm]      = useState({ resolutionStatus: '', notes: '' });
const [editSaving, setEditSaving]  = useState(false);

// Delete confirm modal
const [deleteTarget, setDeleteTarget] = useState(null);  // incident object | null
const [deleteSaving, setDeleteSaving] = useState(false);
```

Keep all existing filter/search state exactly as-is.

### 3d. Token helper

Place after state declarations:

```js
const getToken = () => localStorage.getItem('accessToken');
```

### 3e. Seeding + Fetch logic (`useEffect` on mount)

```js
const fetchIncidents = useCallback(async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    setApiError('');
    try {
        const res = await axios.get('/api/incident', {
            headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${getToken()}` }
        });
        setIncidents(Array.isArray(res.data) ? res.data : []);
    } catch (err) {
        console.error('Failed to fetch incidents:', err);
        setApiError('Failed to load incidents. Displaying last known data.');
        showToast('Failed to load incidents from server.');
    } finally {
        setLoading(false);
    }
}, []);

useEffect(() => {
    const SEED_FLAG = 'flowguard_incidents_seeded';

    const seedAndFetch = async () => {
        if (!localStorage.getItem(SEED_FLAG)) {
            // First ever load — seed the 12 static incidents
            try {
                const token = getToken();
                for (const inc of STATIC_INCIDENTS) {
                    await axios.post('/api/incident', {
                        camera_location: inc.camera_location,
                        status: inc.status,
                        source: inc.source,
                        severity: inc.severity,
                        person_name: inc.person_name || undefined,
                        confidence_score: inc.confidence_score || undefined,
                        notes: inc.notes || ''
                    }, { headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } });
                }
                localStorage.setItem(SEED_FLAG, 'true');
            } catch (err) {
                console.warn('Seeding failed (server may be empty or token expired):', err.message);
                // Still proceed to fetch whatever is in DB
            }
        }
        await fetchIncidents();
    };

    seedAndFetch();
}, [fetchIncidents]);
```

Note on seeding: the loop is sequential (`await` inside `for...of`) to avoid hammering the server with 12 concurrent POSTs. If seeding fails partway (e.g. token expired), `SEED_FLAG` is not set, so next load retries. If the server is already populated from a previous seed, duplicate rows will appear — this is acceptable for test data. The flag is a one-time guard that only clears if you clear localStorage.

