## File 1: `server/models/IncidentLog.js`

### What changes

Add four columns after `confidence_score`. The `paranoid: true` (soft delete) is already in place and must stay.

```js
severity: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(20),
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: 'Medium'
    // Values the frontend uses: 'Critical' | 'High' | 'Medium' | 'Low'
},
source: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(50),
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: 'Facial Recognition'
    // Values: 'Facial Recognition' | 'Object Detection' | 'Manual'
},
resolutionStatus: {
    type: DataTypes.STRING(50),
    allowNull: false,
    defaultValue: 'Active'
    // Values: 'Active' | 'Investigating' | 'Escalated to Security' | 'Cleared'
},
notes: {
    type: DataTypes.TEXT,
    allowNull: true,
    defaultValue: ''
}
```

### Why these types

- `severity` and `source` are short strings — `STRING(20)` and `STRING(50)` match the existing `status` column pattern.
- `resolutionStatus` needs up to `'Escalated to Security'` (22 chars) so `STRING(50)` gives safe headroom.
- `notes` is free-form text, `TEXT` matches `SecurityLogs.js` pattern for `reviewNotes`.
- All four are `allowNull: true` or have a `defaultValue` because the existing AI `scan-frame` route calls `IncidentLog.create(...)` with only `camera_location`, `status`, `person_name`, `confidence_score`. Adding non-nullable columns without defaults would break that route.

### Sequelize `alter: true` behaviour

`server/index.js` runs `db[name].sync({ alter: true })` on startup for every model. Adding these four columns to the model definition is sufficient — Sequelize will issue `ALTER TABLE incident_logs ADD COLUMN ...` automatically on next server start with no manual migration required.

